{
  "answer": "**Sicily** is the historical place directly addressed (personified) in Allama Iqbal's poem \"Saqaliya\" (Bang-E-Dara Part 2, ch. 21).[^1]\n\nThe poem opens by urging tears for \"the grave of Hejazi civilization,\" evoking the lost glory of Muslim (Arab/Hejazi) culture.[^2] It then shifts to praise Sicily explicitly as \"the honor of the sea\" and \"the cradle of that nation's culture,\" lamenting its ruins as a symbol of that faded Islamic splendor in the Mediterranean.[^3][^4]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 \"Saqaliya\" (translation), [p-379aeb](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-379aeb).\n[^2]: Ibid., [p-08760e](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-08760e).\n[^3]: Ibid., [p-82cbe3](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-82cbe3).\n[^4]: \"Saqaliya\" (Sicily) refers to the island's era under Muslim rule (9th–11th centuries), when it was a center of Arab-Islamic civilization; the poem mourns its decline after Norman conquest. Full chapter: [ch. 21](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/).",
